cA.jpeg 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*PzWFzIp-lVCCMv96aWWqcA.jpeg 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*PzWFzIp-lVCCMv96aWWqcA.jpeg 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*PzWFzIp-lVCCMv96aWWqcA.jpeg 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:700/1*PzWFzIp-lVCCMv96aWWqcA.jpeg 700w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:350/1*PzWFzIp-lVCCMv96aWWqcA.jpeg"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">A typical math proof</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">What is a proof?</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A proof is a logical argument that tries to show that a statement is true. In math, and computer science, a proof has to be well thought out and tested before being accepted. But even then, a proof can be <a href="https://mathoverflow.net/questions/35468/widely-accepted-mathematical-results-that-were-later-shown-wrong" target="_self">discovered to have been wrong</a>. There are many different ways to go about proving something, we’ll discuss 3 methods: direct proof, proof by contradiction, proof by induction. We’ll talk about what each of these proofs are, when and how they’re used.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Before diving in, we’ll need to explain some terminology.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">A <strong>theorem</strong> is a mathematical statement which is proven to be true.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;"><mark>A statement that has been proven true in order to further help in proving another statement is called a </mark><mark>lemma</mark><mark>.</mark></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Now that we’ve gotten that out of the way, let’s job into some types of proofs!</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
